<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="140" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1701,2016]" pageId="11" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,1702,1728]" pageId="11" pageNumber="140">Etymology:</emphasis>
The generic name combines two Quechua words (
<emphasis box="[860,907,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="140">qori</emphasis>
= gold, and 
<emphasis box="[1048,1109,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="140">mayu</emphasis>
= river, stream), in reference to ‘Río Oro’, the valley in the Famatina range where all collecting sites are located; grammatical gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
